Generating Synthetic Data from a Simple Biophysical Simulation¶

Author: Kyriacos Nicolaou (kyriakosn24@gmail.com)
Updated: 12th of December, 2024

Introduction¶

We want to fit Log-Gaussian Cox Process (LGCP) model to capture the underlying biophysical characteristics of particle "puncta" generated in a simulated cellular environment. To achieve this, we construct a stochastic biophysical model of particles diffusing within a crowded cell. The presence of intracellular crowders creates spatial heterogeneity in particle density, and our goal is to evaluate whether an LGCP model can recover this heterogeneity from the simulated particle locations obtained over multiple simulation runs.

Model¶

We simulate particle diffusion within a two-dimensional representation of the cell interior. The cell is modeled as the region between two concentric circles: the inner circle represents the cell nucleus, and the outer circle represents the cell membrane. Particles are introduced at the nuclear boundary at a specified production rate. After their introduction, they diffuse through the cytosol with a given diffusion coefficient and are eventually degraded at a certain rate.

To mimic the complexity of the intracellular environment, we include a number of randomly placed small discs ("crowders") in the cytosol. These crowders represent obstacles that cause particles to reflect upon contact, thereby creating non-uniform particle distributions over time. By analyzing these distributions with an LGCP model, we aim to infer the underlying spatial heterogeneity introduced by the crowders.

Simulation class¶

The code for the simulation can be found in the file simulation.py which is in the same folder (notebooks/). In the file we define the simulation class whose objects are initialized with the parameters of the simulation. These parameters are the cell radius, the nucleus radius, the radius of each crowder, the mean density of crowders, the diffusion coeficient of particles, their total production rate and their degradation rate and a the timestep.

PRODUCTION_RATE = 100
DEGRADATION_RATE = 1
DIFFUSION_COEFFICIENT = 0.3
DT = 0.001

sim.plot(axes[0], plot_cell=True, plot_nucleus=True, plot_crowders=True, plot_particles=True)

sim.plot(axes[1], plot_cell=True, plot_nucleus=True, plot_crowders=False, plot_particles=True)
axes[1].set_title("snapshot w/o crowders",size = 11)

plt.show()

From the left plot above: we see how the crowders exclude the particles and on the plot on the right, by hidding the crowders we see that there are hotspots and cold spots of particles .

Now we will run a collection of simulations and keep their final state as realizations of the generating process of particles¶

In [14]:
n_simulations = 9

simulations = []

N_TIMESTEPS = 10000

for sim_i in range(n_simulations):
    sim = sim = Simulation(CELL_RADIUS, NUCLEUS_RADIUS, 
                           CROWDER_RADIUS,MEAN_DENSITY_OF_CROWDERS, 
                           PRODUCTION_RATE,DEGRADATION_RATE,DIFFUSION_COEFFICIENT, DT)

    sim.simulate(N_TIMESTEPS)
    simulations.append(sim)

In [19]:
class SpatialData():
    def __init__(self,x,y):
        self.x = x
        self.y = y

    def shift(self,dx,dy):
        self.x = [i_x + dx for i_x in self.x ]
        self.y = [i_y + dy for i_y in self.y ]

angles = np.linspace(0,2*np.pi,30)
cell_contour_x = CELL_RADIUS*np.cos(np.linspace(0,2*np.pi,30))
cell_contour_x[-1] = cell_contour_x[0]
cell_contour_y = CELL_RADIUS*np.sin(np.linspace(0,2*np.pi,30))
cell_contour_y[-1] = cell_contour_y[0]

cell_contour = SpatialData(cell_contour_x,cell_contour_y)

nucleus_contour_x = NUCLEUS_RADIUS*np.cos(np.linspace(0,2*np.pi,30))
nucleus_contour_x[-1] = nucleus_contour_x[0]
nucleus_contour_y = NUCLEUS_RADIUS*np.sin(np.linspace(0,2*np.pi,30))
nucleus_contour_y[-1] = nucleus_contour_y[0]

nucleus_contour = SpatialData(nucleus_contour_x,nucleus_contour_y)

pad_length = CELL_RADIUS/2

dimension_length = (CELL_RADIUS +pad_length)*2
half_dimension_length = dimension_length/2

box_dimension = dimension_length*0.9
half_box_dimension = box_dimension/2

box_coordinates_x  = np.array([-half_box_dimension, -half_box_dimension,half_box_dimension , half_box_dimension, -half_box_dimension])
box_coordinates_y  = np.array([-half_box_dimension, half_box_dimension, half_box_dimension, -half_box_dimension,-half_box_dimension])

box_contour = SpatialData(box_coordinates_x,box_coordinates_y)

# these contours are identical across all the cells, so we make lists of copies

for ssd in simulation_spatial_data:
    ssd["cell"] = SpatialData(cell_contour_x,cell_contour_y)
    ssd["nucleus"] = SpatialData(nucleus_contour_x,nucleus_contour_y)
    ssd["box"] = SpatialData(box_coordinates_x,box_coordinates_y)
    particle_x,particle_y = ssd["simulation object"].get_particle_coordinates()

    ssd["particles"] =  SpatialData(particle_x,particle_y)

    ssd["extent"] = {"left": -half_dimension_length, 
                     "right" : half_dimension_length,
                     "bot" : -half_dimension_length,
                     "top" : half_dimension_length,                    
                    } 

extent = [-half_dimension_length,half_dimension_length,-half_dimension_length,half_dimension_length]

resolution = 0.01

number_of_pixels = int(np.ceil(dimension_length/resolution))

pixels_x  = np.linspace(-half_dimension_length+resolution/2,half_dimension_length-resolution/2,number_of_pixels) 
pixels_y  = np.linspace(half_dimension_length -resolution/2,-half_dimension_length+resolution/2,number_of_pixels) 

xv, yv = np.meshgrid(pixels_x, pixels_y)

nucleus_distance = np.sqrt(xv*xv + yv*yv) - NUCLEUS_RADIUS
nucleus_distance = nucleus_distance*( (nucleus_distance > 0) * (nucleus_distance < CELL_RADIUS - NUCLEUS_RADIUS))
nucleus_distance_images = n_simulations*[nucleus_distance]

for ssd in simulation_spatial_data:
    ssd["nucleus distance"] = nucleus_distance

for ssd in simulation_spatial_data:
    crowders_image = np.zeros((number_of_pixels,number_of_pixels))
    for crowder in ssd["simulation object"].crowders:
        crowders_image[ np.sqrt((xv-crowder.center.x)**2 + (yv-crowder.center.y)**2) < crowder.radius] = 1
    
    crowders_image = crowders_image*( (nucleus_distance > 0) * (nucleus_distance < CELL_RADIUS - NUCLEUS_RADIUS))
    ssd["crowders"] = crowders_image



for ssd in simulation_spatial_data:
    ssd["resolution"] = resolution

Stich together particle locations and images¶

In [26]:
import numpy as np


aggregated_data = {}

# Create each row by horizontally stacking 3 images

for image in ["crowders","nucleus distance"]:
    row1 = np.hstack((simulation_spatial_data[6][image], simulation_spatial_data[7][image], simulation_spatial_data[8][image]))
    row2 = np.hstack((simulation_spatial_data[3][image], simulation_spatial_data[4][image], simulation_spatial_data[5][image]))
    row3 = np.hstack((simulation_spatial_data[0][image], simulation_spatial_data[1][image], simulation_spatial_data[2][image]))

    aggregated_data[image] =  np.vstack((row1, row2, row3))

aggregated_data["resolution"] = resolution

aggregated_data["extent"] = {}

aggregated_data["extent"] = {"left": -half_dimension_length, 
                     "right" :-half_dimension_length + 3*dimension_length,
                     "bot" :  -half_dimension_length,
                     "top" :   -half_dimension_length + 3*dimension_length,                    
                    } 

aggregated_data_extent = [aggregated_data["extent"][direction] for direction in ["left","right","bot","top"]]

shifts_vector = np.array([0,dimension_length,2*dimension_length ])
x_shifts_v, y_shifts_v = np.meshgrid(shifts_vector, shifts_vector)
In [28]:
for component in ["cell","nucleus","box"]:
    aggregated_data[component] = []
    for ssd, x_shift, y_shift in zip(simulation_spatial_data, x_shifts_v.flatten(),y_shifts_v.flatten()):
        component_copy = SpatialData(ssd[component].x,ssd[component].y)
        component_copy.shift(x_shift,y_shift)
        aggregated_data[component].append(component_copy)


aggregated_data["particles"] = SpatialData([],[])
for ssd, x_shift, y_shift in zip(simulation_spatial_data, x_shifts_v.flatten(),y_shifts_v.flatten()):
    component_copy = SpatialData(ssd["particles"].x,ssd["particles"].y)
    component_copy.shift(x_shift,y_shift)
    aggregated_data["particles"].x = aggregated_data["particles"].x + component_copy.x
    aggregated_data["particles"].y = aggregated_data["particles"].y + component_copy.y

domain_polygons = []
for cell,nucleus in zip(aggregated_data["cell"],aggregated_data["nucleus"]):
    p1 = shapely.geometry.Polygon(zip(nucleus.x, nucleus.y))
    p2 = shapely.geometry.Polygon(zip(cell.x, cell.y))
    domain_polygons.append(shapely.geometry.Polygon(p2.exterior.coords, [p1.exterior.coords]))


contour_dicitonary = {'ID': np.arange(1,10).tolist(), 'geometry': domain_polygons}

transform = rasterio.transform.from_origin(aggregated_data["extent"]["left"],
                                           aggregated_data["extent"]["top"], 
                                           aggregated_data["resolution"], 
                                           aggregated_data["resolution"])

with rasterio.open("../data/synthetic_data/diffusion_in_crowded_enviroment/crowders.tif", 
                   'w', 
                   driver='GTiff',
                   height=aggregated_data["crowders"].shape[0], width=aggregated_data["crowders"].shape[1], 
                   count=1,
